    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3fa8b620_f0caeb9e",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003190
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-03T18:05:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Bikeshedding about function order:\n\nI advocate putting public functions at the top, and helper functions nearby below; when first scanning a file, I think most people start at the top, and want to get an overall idea of the main public functions there. Then, when digging into the implementation, they may look below to see the implementation of a helper function.\n\nI think that the main reason for the tradition of putting helper functions above main functions is that some languages required declarations/definitions before use (e.g. C).",
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "110fb012_7e676b73",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003190
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-03T20:07:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Follow-up note: If the general convention in the code-base the helper-then-main order, then it\u0027s alright to put functions in that order to keep the code consistent.\n\nAnyway, just something to think about.",
      "parentUuid": "3fa8b620_f0caeb9e",
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "646850a0_a72389df",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-04T18:45:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My general convention (coming from python) is\n\n\u003cimports\u003e\n\n\u003cconsts\u003e\n\n\u003cstructs\u003e\n\n\u003cstuff\u003e\n\n\u003cmain entry point implementation\u003e\n\n\u003cmain entry point redirector\u003e\n\nThis is because I start scanning a file from the bottom and go upwards.  I think i\u0027ve seen this ordering in some other parts of LogDog code also.",
      "parentUuid": "110fb012_7e676b73",
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
