    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7aba6e25_b6f97e0e",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 1109829
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-03T21:30:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I actually want to double back on making these members of \"logData\" (or \"logFetchOperation\"). At this point, we have a collection of variables representing a well-defined state. This is exactly what structs and struct methods are for. I\u0027d make the operation contain all of these variables. Nice benefit: you don\u0027t have to forward most of them to \"fetchOnce\".",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 122,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 122,
        "endChar": 10
      },
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8bb4d37d_09ed7a51",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-04T18:45:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I made logData a copy of ls and lst instead.  I did this explicitly to signal to the reader what the lifecycle of each variable is supposed to be.  I think it\u0027s easier to follow this way.",
      "parentUuid": "7aba6e25_b6f97e0e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 122,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 122,
        "endChar": 10
      },
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "94396ff7_6830d4a9",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 126,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003190
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-03T18:05:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "between fetches from storage.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 126,
        "startChar": 44,
        "endLine": 126,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d1da1b20_a664f8df",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 126,
      "author": {
        "id": 1109829
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-03T21:30:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I mentioned in a previous comment that you should use the \"retry\" library for this. Is there a reason you chose not to? It will handle error cases, sleeping, Context cancellation, and backoff execution and tuning, and the rest of LogDog code uses it for this reason.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 126,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 126,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "185ae55b_e048777b",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 126,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-04T18:45:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes.  I did it for readability.  From a reader\u0027s view, using retry requires understanding the intricacies of two additional libraries, following an anonymous function, and adding several layers of indentation to the code.  As a reader of logdog code, following the flow for retry.Retry was one of my biggest pain points, and I wanted to avoid that.\n\nIn python, this was a simple decorator\n@retry(a, b, c, d)\ndef foo(...):\n  ...\n\nBut in Go, the boilerplate code for adding in a retry.Retry is almost as much as the code to inline it.  But by inlining the code, the reader does not have to context-switch to figure out what is going on.",
      "parentUuid": "d1da1b20_a664f8df",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 126,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 126,
        "endChar": 51
