      "lineNbr": 126,
      "author": {
        "id": 1109829
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-04T23:03:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Retry is pretty fundamental, and is used everywhere else in LogDog application and library code. Rolling your own sort of violates the existing style, and obviates the library\u0027s purpose, which is to handle retries.\n\nIf you feel strongly that \"retry\" is difficult to read, I\u0027d suggest that you improve it (or, alternatively, tear it out and implement custom retries everywhere); however, I don\u0027t think it\u0027s a good idea to have case by case reimplementations of an otherwise pervasive standard.\n\nI think the readability is pretty straightforward:\n\nretryParams :\u003d retry.ExponentialBackoff{}\nretry.Retry(c, func(...) { ... }, retryParams, untilLogIsFinished)\n\nTo me, that reads \"retry using exponential backoff until the log is finished\".",
      "parentUuid": "185ae55b_e048777b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 126,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 126,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4c09e99f_b930d9b2",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 126,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-10T23:45:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Was halfway done with a retry.Retry implementation before I realized.. It still doesn\u0027t make sense.\n\nThe original fetcher used a forever loop:\nhttps://cs.chromium.org/chromium/infra/go/src/go.chromium.org/luci/logdog/common/fetcher/fetcher.go?q\u003dfetcher+logdog\u0026sq\u003dpackage:chromium\u0026dr\u003dCSs\u0026l\u003d366\nI don\u0027t think it\u0027s common to use retry.Retry for \"loop until done\".\n\nretry.Retry has been used for calls that are expected to run once on the normative case, none of the options available are suited for running forever with the exact set of things we want here.  The documentation literally says:\n\"Retry executes a function \u0027fn\u0027. If the function returns an error, it will be re-executed according to a retry plan.\"\n\nThat means for retry.Retry to work here, the inner function has to return a fake error that isn\u0027t really an error.  This smells a lot like \"raise ndb.Return(...)\".\n\nIn addition, the logic we have here is to exponential backoff only if no new logs were fetched, and use a 1s backoff otherwise, and reset the exponential backoff counter.  That would require a pretty custom retry.Factory already, which probably would make this much longer than this code.\n\n(digression) As for improving the egronomics of retry.Retry, I\u0027d probably add a new set of retry \"engines\", which are prefilled with options.  Eg.\nretry.OnTransientFailure(c, func() {...})\nOr make an engine factory, \nretry.With(Exponential, Logging, TransientOnly).On(c, func() {...})\nI think this would make it easier to read.",
      "parentUuid": "65dc96ac_75bedf68",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 126,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 126,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "af60ac12d61b409eee25b77f4f60d806d775d02a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "310ef30a_a5082f66",
        "filename": "logdog/appengine/coordinator/flex/logs/http.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 126,
      "author": {
        "id": 1109829
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-05-11T13:37:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "RE sentinel error, totally, but that\u0027s part of the design of the library. The library supports transience functionality because it is such a common use case for retry, but it is (by design) not limited to transient retries. Case in point: one must opt into transient retries.\n\nYou are correct - you\u0027d want to create a sentinel error. Actually, it looks like iannucci@\u0027s refactor of transience made it a little harder to do by moving my Once function into a subpackage:\nhttps://chromium.googlesource.com/infra/luci/luci-go/+/a67367ced1a85b53d7a96e7c4c91ef5d66c9c6e3/common/retry/transient/transient.go#64\n\nPrior to that, all you\u0027d have to do is say something like:\nvar errWaitingForMoreLogs \u003d errors.New(\"waiting for more logs\")\n\nvar exp retry.Exponential{...}\nretry.Retry(..., retry.On(errWaitingForMoreLogs, exp))\n\nIf you\u0027re interested, I threw this together to add it back:\nhttps://chromium-review.googlesource.com/#/c/infra/luci/luci-go/+/1054474\n\nSentinel errors aren\u0027t really bad - they\u0027re part of the intended usage of Go\u0027s error functionality (e.g., io.EOF).\n\n---\n\nThat said, the reason I care about this at all is that \"retry\" and its backoff generation are scoped and tested. This ad-hoc backoff is not really. You can add tests and assert that it exponentially backs off, or you can use the backoff iterator. The latter, to me, is both more consistent and simpler.\n\nI do like your retry construction. That\u0027d be a good refactor.",
      "parentUuid": "4c09e99f_b930d9b2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 126,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 126,
        "endChar": 51
      },
